keywords = {Artificial intelligence, EU, digital market, normative power, liability},
abstract = {On April 1, 2021, the European Union (EU) Commission accepted the proposal for the artificial intelligence (AI) regulation, which is considered to be the first legal regulation on AI. On January 9th, The Digital Decade policy program 2030, a monitoring and cooperation mechanism to achieve common targets for Europe’s digital transformation by 2030, entered into force. After approval by the EU Parliament, the regulation will enter into direct force in all member states and will bring obligations for many sectors. A two-year implementation period is envisaged for transition and updates on the future needs of AI. The AI regulation, along with other EU regulations in the digital sector such as Data Governance Law, Digital Services Law, and Digital Markets Law, contributes to digital policy reform of the EU. The regulation is significant as it broadly defines “AI systems” and imposes specific obligations on actors of the AI chain. In addition, the regulation contains provisions to promote development and uptake of AI systems in the EU. Also, the European AI Board is established to supervise and coordinate the use of artificial intelligence systems on the EU level for all internal markets and EU citizens. The regulation will have an outstanding impact on its scope beyond the EU borders. The European principles or norms are enshrined in the acquis communitaire, meaning the EU’s body of law. They include the centrality of peace, liberty, democracy, supranational rule of law, and human rights. These aspects enable the EU to maintain its normative power for the foreseeable future by pioneering regulatory process in high-tech markets as a result of the codification of its norms as binding agreements.}
}
