abstract = {Emerging technologies in recent decades have transformed the provisioning of goods and services in a variety of sectors, including health care. These technologies are evolving continuously and have the potential for groundbreaking discoveries and practical applications. However, the novelty, speed, and drastic changes that are brought about by new technologies also result in several uncertainties about how new products and services may affect people’s personal health, societal norms, and the environment. Artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML) technologies can be problematic because people can fail to use them appropriately. Since people respond to technology socially, trust influences reliance on automation to a great extent. Performance in delivering effective healthcare outcomes using technology depends largely on appropriate levels of trust being established between humans and their automated agents. A better understanding of human-automation trust can have important implications for the design of AI healthcare frameworks and for training individuals for effective and satisfying interaction with such systems. Against the background of the gender digital divide in the access to and use of technology, the rise of AI and ML in the healthcare sector has important implications for women. While AI has the potential to revolutionize diagnostic and assistive care for women, it still must navigate the trust barrier in assuring and securing a widespread usability by women in all age groups. This chapter looks at the human-automation trust in AI-enabled health care for women. It examines the contextual factors favoring and inhibiting trust with a focus on socioeconomic determinants, decision-making power, and risk perceptions towards AI. The study makes several policy recommendations for the calibration of trust in the use of AI in women’s health care.}
