keywords = {Artificial intelligence, Benefits, Challenges, COVID-19 pandemic, Digital health, Innovation, Potential, Prediction},
abstract = {The COVID-19 pandemic has posed significant challenges to healthcare systems and providers, requiring them to address new and acute needs while ensuring the continuity of primary services. Digital health solutions, particularly those employing artificial intelligence (AI) technologies, have demonstrated their potential to enhance, support, and address these challenges. AI technologies can decentralize services, increase existing system capacities, alleviate healthcare strain, prioritize patient triage, predict disease risk and progression, and expedite drug and vaccine discovery. Ultimately, these technologies aim to reduce morbidity and mortality while improving the quality of care and patients' quality of life. Various examples illustrate AI's benefits, from predicting pandemic trends and disease prevention to virtual assistance, early infection diagnosis, COVID-19 treatment prognostication, and remote monitoring systems that alert physicians to patient deterioration. However, it is crucial to acknowledge the significant challenges associated with developing and scaling up these solutions. Factors to consider include data collection and study size, data quality, validation and reproducibility, ethical issues (e.g., data protection, privacy, patient consent, and ethical use), introduction of biases, potential discrimination, barriers to technology implementation, and fostering trust and acceptance among patients and providers. While AI technologies' potential and benefits are undeniable, their implementation and scaling up must be thoughtfully executed. A holistic approach is necessary to ensure these innovative solutions can truly deliver the desired outcomes.}
